          "body": "Verses 6-7 contain one of the most theologically dense reversals in the Psalter. God Himself is the speaker: 'I said, You are gods, and all of you are sons of the Most High.' The divine citation (*'amarti*, I said) is solemn — God recalls His own prior act of appointment. The title 'gods' (*elohim*) and 'sons of the Most High' (*bene Elyon*) represent the highest dignity that can be conferred on a creature: to bear the divine name by delegation, to act as God's authorized representative on earth. Then verse 7 detonates the reversal: *akhen* — 'Nevertheless.' The adversative is the harshest in biblical Hebrew, used to shatter a false premise. Whatever the title conferred, the conduct has disqualified the bearers from its protection. 'You will die like men and fall like any one of the princes.' The sentence strips away every illusion of transcendence. Jonathan Edwards noted that the most dangerous spiritual position is to hold a high title from God while living in a manner that contradicts it — the gap between title and life is what makes the judgment more severe, not less. The rulers' mortality is not an insult; it is the just sentence on those who were given godlike authority and used it for ungodlike ends."
