          "body": "The psalm's closing verse is not a coda — it is the whole point. Having seen God stand in the assembly (v. 1), having heard the accusation (vv. 2-4), the evidence (v. 5), and the sentence (vv. 6-7), the psalmist turns from the heavenly courtroom to the visible earth and cries: *Qumah Elohim, shafetah ha-aretz* — 'Arise, O God, judge the earth!' The petition assumes that what has been adjudicated in the divine assembly has not yet been fully executed on earth. Corrupt rulers still stand; the weak are still oppressed; the foundations still shake. The space between the heavenly verdict and the earthly execution is exactly where the believer lives — and exactly where this petition arises. The closing ground (*ki*, 'for') is a confession of faith: 'You possess all the nations as Your inheritance.' God's jurisdiction is universal, not tribal. The psalm that began in the divine assembly ends with a claim over every nation that has ever existed. Calvin notes that this petition is not despair but faith — it is precisely because the believer knows God has already judged in the assembly that he can pray with confidence for that judgment to fall on the earth."
