        "body": "Verse 5 is the psalm's pivotal diagnosis. It explains *why* the rulers have failed and names the consequence of their failure. The explanation is epistemological: *they do not know nor do they understand*. The Hebrew verbs *yada* and *bin* are not ignorance of trivial matters — they are the knowledge and discernment that the Old Testament consistently requires of those who govern. Proverbs 8:15-16 presents wisdom as the prerequisite of just rule: 'By me kings reign and rulers decree justice... by me princes govern.' The rulers of Psalm 82 have rejected this wisdom; they walk in *chashekhah*, moral darkness — the opposite of the light of Torah (Psalm 119:105).\n\nThis is willful ignorance, not innocent confusion. The Mosaic law was not hidden; the covenant standard was publicly known. The rulers' darkness is the darkness of those who refuse to see, not those who lack access to light (cf. John 3:19-20, where Jesus uses the same moral framework). Peter Davids's analysis of James 1:5 is relevant: the rulers did not ask God for the wisdom He freely gives; they substituted their own judgment for His.\n\nThe consequence is architecturally terrifying: 'all the foundations of the earth are shaken.' The *mosedei erets* (foundations of the earth) is the Old Testament's image for the moral and structural order God built into creation (Psalm 75:3; Proverbs 8:29; Isaiah 24:18-20). When those who are appointed to uphold justice invert it, the structural floor of civilized life is undermined. The image is seismic — not metaphorically shaken but cosmically destabilized. John Calvin saw in this verse the theological explanation for why every era of history produces social collapse: unjust governance is not merely an administrative failure; it is an assault on the order God embedded in creation itself.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yada* — to know, to discern relationally and practically. *Bin* — to understand, to perceive the distinctions; the root of *binah* (discernment). *Chashekhah* — darkness, the realm of moral blindness. *Mosad* — foundation, the structural base; plural *mosedei* appears also in Psalm 18:7 and 75:3 in seismic contexts. *Mot* — to shake, to totter, to be moved."
